ambridge and New York | publisher=Cambridge University Press | isbn=978-1-10700-906-6|ref=harv}}\n*{{citation|chapter=Nation versus Army: A necessary contrast? |last=Kulikowski |first=Michael |page=69-84 |title=On barbarian identity. Critical approaches to ethnicity in the early middle ages|editor-last=Gillett |editor-first=Andrew |publication-place= Turnhout |year=2002}}\n* {{cite book | last=Larned | first= J. N., ed. | year=1895 | title= History for Ready Reference | place= Cambridge, MA| publisher= C.A. Nichols | ref= harv }}\n* {{citation|title=Claudian's In Eutropium: Or, How, When, and Why to Slander a Eunuch |first=Jacqueline |last=Long |year=1996 |chapter=5 |url=https://books.google.be/books?id=E-U6CwAAQBAJ}}\n* {{cite book| last=Oman | first=Charles W.C | year=1902 | title= The Byzantine Empire | place=New York | publisher= G.P. Putnam\u2019s Sons | ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book| last=Todd | first=Malcolm | year=1999 | title= The Early Germans | place= Oxford | publisher= Blackwell | isbn=0-631-16397-2 | ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book | last1=Waldman | first1=Carl | last2=Mason | first2 = Allan R. | title=Encyclopedia of European Peoples | year=2006 | location=New York | publisher=Facts on File |  isbn=978-0-81604-964-6 | ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book | last=Wallace-Hadrill | first=J. M. | title=The Barbarian West, 400\u20131000 | year=2004 | place=Malden, MA | publisher=Wiley-Blackwell | isbn=978-0-63120-292-9 | ref=harv}} \n* {{cite book | last=Wolfram | first=Herwig | year=1988 | title=History of the Goths | place=Berkeley and Los Angeles| publisher=University of California Press | isbn= 978-0-52006-983-1 | ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book | last=Wolfram | first=Herwig | year=1997 | title=The Roman Empire and its Germanic Peoples | place=Berkeley and Los Angeles| publisher=University of California Press | isbn= 0-520-08511-6 | ref= harv }}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Commons category-inline|Ostrogoths}}\n\n{{-}}\n{{Germanic peoples}}\n\n[[Category:Ostrogoths| ]]\n[[Category:Early Germanic peoples]]\n[[Category:History of the Balkans]]\n[[Category:Ancient Italian history]]\n\n[[de:Goten#Ostgoten]]\n", "name_user": "Andrew Lancaster", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEtymology", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ostrogoths"}
{"title_page": "Happy Birthday Sweet Sixteen", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Happy Birthday Sweet Sixteen\n| cover      = Happy Birthday Sweet 16.JPG\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Italian release of \"Happy Birthday Sweet Sixteen\"\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Neil Sedaka]]\n| album      = [[Neil Sedaka Sings His Greatest Hits]]\n| B-side     = Don't Lead Me On\n| released   = November 1961\n| format     = 45 rpm single\n| recorded   = 1961\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| length     = 2:40\n| label      = [[RCA Victor]]\n| writer     = Neil Sedaka and [[Howard Greenfield]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = Sweet Little You\n| prev_year  = 1961\n| next_title = King of Clowns\n| next_year  = 1962\n}}\n\"'''Happy Birthday Sweet Sixteen'''\" is a [[pop music|pop]] song released in 1961 by [[Neil Sedaka]]. Sedaka wrote the music and performed the song, while the lyrics were written by [[Howard Greenfield]]. The song is noted for being similar in musical structure to [[Take Good Care of My Baby]] by [[Bobby Vee]] (another 1961 hit), and additionally for its resemblance to the melody of the [[Chiffons]]' subsequent 1963 hit \"[[One Fine Day (song)|One Fine Day]]\". Both of these songs exhibiting similarity to \"Happy Birthday Sweet Sixteen\" were penned by the team of [[Carole King]] and [[Gerry Goffin]]. The song reached #6 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart<ref>[http://www.history-of-rock.com/neil_sedaka.htm History of Rock: Neil Sedaka]</ref> and no 3 on the [[UK Singles Chart]].\n\nThe narrator sings the song to a childhood friend of his upon her sixteenth birthday, reminiscing about the ups and downs of their friendship thus far and declaring that now that she has grown from an awkward tomboy into a beautiful young lady, he wants her for his girlfriend.\n\nThis was one of several Sedaka recordings that employed the services of drummer [[Gary Chester]].<ref>http://www.angelfire.com/music5/garychester/disc.html</ref> Other musicians on the record include Al Casamenti, Art Reyerson and Charles Macey on guitar, Ernie Hayes on piano, George Duviver on bass, Artie Kaplan on sax, Seymour Barab and Morris Stonzek on cellos, David Guillet, Joseph Haber, Louie Haber, Harold Kohon, David Sackson, Maurice Stine, Louis Stone, and Arnold Goldberg on violins, and Phil Kraus and George Devens on percussion.\n\n==Chart history==\n{{col-begin|width=71%}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1961\u201362)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Australia \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n|-\n|Canada ([[CHUM (AM)|CHUM]] ''Hit Parade'')<ref>[http://chumtribute.com/61-12-11-chart.jpg CHUM ''Hit Parade'', December 11, 1961]</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|7\n|-\n|Japan <ref name=\"History of Rock: Neil Sedaka\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n|New Zealand (''Lever Hit Parade'')<ref>[http://www.flavourofnz.co.nz/index.php?qpageID=search%20lever&qsongid=175#n_view_location NZ Lever Hit Parade, 23 March 1961]</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|7\n|-\n|[[UK Singles Chart|UK]] <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/28079/neil-sedaka/ |title=Official Charts Company |website=Officialcharts.com |date=1961-12-27 |accessdate=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|U.S. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]]<ref>''Joel Whitburn's Top Pop Singles 1955\u20131990'' - {{ISBN|0-89820-089-X}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|6\n|-\n|U.S. [[Cash Box (magazine)|''Cash Box'']] Top 100\n|align=\"center\"|9\n|-\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1961)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Rank\n|-\n|UK <ref>[http://www.sixtiescity.net/charts/62chart.htm#top100 The 100 Best-Selling Singles of 1962]</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|33\n|-\n|US ([[Joel Whitburn]]'s ''Pop Annual'')<ref>{{cite book |last=Whitburn |first=Joel |date=1999 |title=Pop Annual |url= |location=Menomonee Falls, Wisconsin |publisher=Record Research Inc. |page= |isbn=0-89820-142-X}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|60\n|-\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Other versions==\n* A [[Bobby Vee]] version was released on the album \"30 Big Hits from the 60's\" in 1964.\n* The [[Sweden|Swedish]] [[dansband]] [[Flamingokvintetten]] in 1968 recorded a [[cover version|cover]] of the song that reached #1 in the Swedish charts [[Tio i topp]] and [[Kv\u00e4llstoppen]]. They also recorded a [[Swedish language|Swedish]] version of the song, named \"Hon \u00e4r sexton \u00e5r i dag\" reaching [[Svensktoppen]] the same year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sverigesradio.se/Diverse/AppData/Isidor/files/2023/3465.txt|title=Svensktoppen|year=1968|accessdate=25 May 2011}}</ref>\n* A version called \"Happy Birthday, Twenty-One\" with a special lyric by [[Ian Whitcomb]] and sung by [[Mae West]] was released on her ''[[Great Balls of Fire (Mae West album)|Great Balls of Fire]]'' album in 1972 on [[MGM Records]].\n* In 2009, Damian McGinty of [[Celtic Thunder]] included the song on their album ''Take Me Home''.\n* In the ''[[Roseanne (TV series)|Roseanne]]'' episode \"Pretty in Black\" (Season Five), [[Roseanne Barr|Roseanne]], [[John Goodman|Dan]] and several of their friends sing the first chorus of this song to a mortified [[Sara Gilbert|Darlene]] at her \"sweet sixteen\" party.  A version of the song by an uncredited performer is also played over the closing credits of the episode.\n*In an episode of King of Queens Arthur Spooner, played by Jerry Stiller claims that he inspired Sedaka to this song. In the end of this episode Sedaka appears as himself.\n*[[Chilling Adventures of Sabrina (TV series)|The Chilling Adventures of Sabrina]] used the song in their first trailer.<ref>{{Citation|last=Netflix|title=Chilling Adventures of Sabrina {{!}} Official Trailer [HD] {{!}} Netflix|date=2018-10-03|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ybKUX6thF8Q|access-date=2018-10-03}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n4^https://www.afmsagaftrafund.org/covered-rec-artist_SR.php?a=MDI4MjEx&b=SEFQUFkgQklSVEhEQVksIFNXRUVUIFNJWFRFRU4%3D&c=U0VEQUtBIE5FSUw%3D&s=Rg%3D%3D\n{{Neil Sedaka}}\n\n[[Category:1961 songs]]\n[[Category:Neil Sedaka songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Neil Sedaka]]\n[[Category:Songs with lyrics by Howard Greenfield]]\n[[Category:Flamingokvintetten songs]]\n[[Category:RCA Victor singles]]\n\n{{1960s-pop-song-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Happy Birthday Sweet Sixteen\n| cover      = Happy Birthday Sweet 16.JPG\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Italian release of \"Happy Birthday Sweet Sixteen\"\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Neil Sedaka]]\n| album      = [[Neil Sedaka Sings His Greatest Hits]]\n| B-side     = Don't Lead Me On\n| released   = November 1961\n| format     = 45 rpm single\n| recorded   = 1961\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| length     = 2:40\n| label      = [[RCA Victor]]\n| writer     = Neil Sedaka and [[Howard Greenfield]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = Sweet Little You\n| prev_year  = 1961\n| next_title = King of Clowns\n| next_year  = 1962\n}}\n\"'''Happy Birthday Sweet Sixteen'''\" is a [[pop music|pop]] song released in 1961 by [[Neil Sedaka]]. Sedaka wrote the music and performed the song, while the lyrics were written by [[Howard Greenfield]]. The song is noted for being similar in musical structure to [[Take Good Care of My Baby]] by [[Bobby Vee]] (another 1961 hit), and additionally for its resemblance to the melody of the [[Chiffons]]' subsequent 1963 hit \"[[One Fine Day (song)|One Fine Day]]\". Both of these songs exhibiting similarity to \"Happy Birthday Sweet Sixteen\" were penned by the team of [[Carole King]] and [[Gerry Goffin]]. The song reached #6 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart<ref>[http://www.history-of-rock.com/neil_sedaka.htm History of Rock: Neil Sedaka]</ref> and no 3 on the [[UK Singles Chart]].\n\nThe narrator sings the song to a childhood friend of his upon her sixteenth birthday, reminiscing about the ups and downs of their friendship thus far and declaring that now that she has grown from an awkward tomboy into a beautiful young lady, he wants her for his girlfriend.\n\nThis was one of several Sedaka recordings that employed the services of drummer [[Gary Chester]].<ref>http://www.angelfire.com/music5/garychester/disc.html</ref> Other musicians on the record include Al Casamenti, Art Reyerson and Charles Macey on guitar, Ernie Hayes on piano, George Duviver on bass, Artie Kaplan on sax, Seymour Barab and Morris Stonzek on cellos, David Guillet, Joseph Haber, Louie Haber, Harold Kohon, David Sackson, Maurice Stine, Louis Stone, and Arnold Goldberg on violins, and Phil Kraus and George Devens on percussion.\n\n==Chart history==\n{{col-begin|width=71%}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1961\u201362)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Australia \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n|Canada ([[CHUM (AM)|CHUM]] ''Hit Parade'')<ref>[http://chumtribute.com/61-12-11-chart.jpg CHUM ''Hit Parade'', December 11, 1961]</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|7\n|-\n|Japan <ref name=\"History of Rock: Neil Sedaka\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n|New Zealand (''Lever Hit Parade'')<ref>[http://www.flavourofnz.co.nz/index.php?qpageID=search%20lever&qsongid=175#n_view_location NZ Lever Hit Parade, 23 March 1961]</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|7\n|-\n|[[UK Singles Chart|UK]] <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/28079/neil-sedaka/ |title=Official Charts Company |website=Officialcharts.com |date=1961-12-27 |accessdate=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|U.S. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]]<ref>''Joel Whitburn's Top Pop Singles 1955\u20131990'' - {{ISBN|0-89820-089-X}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|6\n|-\n|U.S. [[Cash Box (magazine)|''Cash Box'']] Top 100\n|align=\"center\"|9\n|-\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1961)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Rank\n|-\n|UK <ref>[http://www.sixtiescity.net/charts/62chart.htm#top100 The 100 Best-Selling Singles of 1962]</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|33\n|-\n|US ([[Joel Whitburn]]'s ''Pop Annual'')<ref>{{cite book |last=Whitburn |first=Joel |date=1999 |title=Pop Annual |url= |location=Menomonee Falls, Wisconsin |publisher=Record Research Inc. |page= |isbn=0-89820-142-X}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|60\n|-\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Other versions==\n* A [[Bobby Vee]] version was released on the album \"30 Big Hits from the 60's\" in 1964.\n* The [[Sweden|Swedish]] [[dansband]] [[Flamingokvintetten]] in 1968 recorded a [[cover version|cover]] of the song that reached #1 in the Swedish charts [[Tio i topp]] and [[Kv\u00e4llstoppen]]. They also recorded a [[Swedish language|Swedish]] version of the song, named \"Hon \u00e4r sexton \u00e5r i dag\" reaching [[Svensktoppen]] the same year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sverigesradio.se/Diverse/AppData/Isidor/files/2023/3465.txt|title=Svensktoppen|year=1968|accessdate=25 May 2011}}</ref>\n* A version called \"Happy Birthday, Twenty-One\" with a special lyric by [[Ian Whitcomb]] and sung by [[Mae West]] was released on her ''[[Great Balls of Fire (Mae West album)|Great Balls of Fire]]'' album in 1972 on [[MGM Records]].\n* In 2009, Damian McGinty of [[Celtic Thunder]] included the song on their album ''Take Me Home''.\n* In the ''[[Roseanne (TV series)|Roseanne]]'' episode \"Pretty in Black\" (Season Five), [[Roseanne Barr|Roseanne]], [[John Goodman|Dan]] and several of their friends sing the first chorus of this song to a mortified [[Sara Gilbert|Darlene]] at her \"sweet sixteen\" party.  A version of the song by an uncredited performer is also played over the closing credits of the episode.\n*In an episode of King of Queens Arthur Spooner, played by Jerry Stiller claims that he inspired Sedaka to this song. In the end of this episode Sedaka appears as himself.\n*[[Chilling Adventures of Sabrina (TV series)|The Chilling Adventures of Sabrina]] used the song in their first trailer.<ref>{{Citation|last=Netflix|title=Chilling Adventures of Sabrina {{!}} Official Trailer [HD] {{!}} Netflix|date=2018-10-03|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ybKUX6thF8Q|access-date=2018-10-03}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n4^https://www.afmsagaftrafund.org/covered-rec-artist_SR.php?a=MDI4MjEx&b=SEFQUFkgQklSVEhEQVksIFNXRUVUIFNJWFRFRU4%3D&c=U0VEQUtBIE5FSUw%3D&s=Rg%3D%3D\n{{Neil Sedaka}}\n\n[[Category:1961 songs]]\n[[Category:Neil Sedaka songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Neil Sedaka]]\n[[Category:Songs with lyrics by Howard Greenfield]]\n[[Category:Flamingokvintetten songs]]\n[[Category:RCA Victor singles]]\n\n{{1960s-pop-song-stub}}\n", "name_user": "JGabbard", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWeekly charts:+ #", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Happy_Birthday_Sweet_Sixteen"}
{"title_page": "Vittoria Puccini", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{BLP sources|date=September 2008}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Vittoria Puccini\n| image       = Vittoria Puccini cropped.jpg\n| caption     = Actress Vittoria Puccini\n| imagesize   = 220px\n| birth_name  = Vittoria Puccini\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1981|11|18|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Florence]], [[Tuscany]], [[Italy]]\n| parents     =\n| occupation  = Actress\n| yearsactive = 2000\u2013present\n| awards      =\n}}\n\n'''Vittoria Puccini''' (born 18 November 1981) is an [[Italy|Italian]] [[film]] and [[television]] [[actress]].\n\nSince her success as the lead actress in 2003 costume drama television series ''Elisa di Rivombrosa'', she has continued to work in television and movie productions, becoming one of the most popular actresses in Italy.\n\nShe has a daughter (born 2006) with Italian actor and ''Elisa di Rivombrosa'' co-star [[Alessandro Preziosi]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}} Her newest production is the television series ''Il Processo'', where she played one of the main roles.\n\n==Filmography==\n'''Cinema'''\n*''[[Tutto l'amore che c'\u00e8]]'', directed by [[Sergio Rubini]] (2000)\n*''[[Paz!]]'', directed by [[Renato De Maria]] (2002)\n*''[[Operazione Appia Antica]]'', directed by [[Carlo Lizzani]] (2003)\n*''[[Ma quando arrivano le ragazze?]]'', directed by [[Pupi Avati]] (2005)\n*''[[Colpo d'occhio]]'', directed by Sergio Rubini (2008)\n*''[[Baciami ancora]]'', directed by [[Gabriele Muccino]] (2010) (2011) \n*''[[La vita facile]]'', directed by [[Lucio Pellegrini]] (2011)\n*''Acciaio'', directed by [[Stefano Mordini]]  (2012)\n*''[[Magnifica presenza]]'', directed by [[Ferzan \u00d6zpetek]] (2012)\n*''[[Tutta colpa di Freud]]'', directed by [[Paolo Genovese]] (2014)\n*''[[The Place (film)|The Place]]'', directed by [[Paolo Genovese]] (2017)\n* [[18 Regali (2020 film)| 18 Regali]], directed by [[Francesco Amato]] (2020)\n\n'''Television''